liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and centrist opposition party leader Benny Gantz have agreed to form an emergency unity government, the two leaders said in a joint statement. The sides have agreed to form a war cabinet comprising Mr Netanyahu, Mr Gantz (a former defence chief) and Defence Minister Yoav Gallant, the statement said. The leaders say that during the fighting with Hamas in Gaza they will not promote any unrelated policies or laws. Reporting by Reuters.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel's Netanyahu, Gantz to form unity government, wartime cabinet

props.alt: An Orthodox Jewish man stands beside a large billboard showing the faces of Benjamin Netanyahu and Benny Gantz, split down the middle.

children.content: An election poster depicts Benny Gantz, right, and Benjamin Netanyahu as rivals during the 2021 Israeli election.
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and centrist opposition party leader Benny Gantz have agreed to form an emergency unity government, the two leaders said in a joint statement.
The sides have agreed to form a war cabinet comprising Mr Netanyahu, Mr Gantz (a former defence chief) and Defence Minister Yoav Gallant, the statement said.
The leaders say that during the fighting with Hamas in Gaza they will not promote any unrelated policies or laws.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Israeli defence force has declared a large portion of southern Israel around the Gaza Strip a "closed military zone" as Israeli soldiers are conducting "combat activity" in the area. "Entry is strictly prohibited and constitutes a serious security risk, as well as a criminal offence," the IDF said in a statement. The ABC's global affairs editor John Lyons says things look "ominous" in Israel as a possible ground invasion of Gaza looms. "360,000 Israeli army reservists have been called up," he told The World's Beverley O'Connor. "To put that into perspective, when Vladimir Putin invaded Ukraine, he amassed about 100,000 Russian troops along the border, and the world thought that was a huge military build-up."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Gaza Ministry of Energy says the territory's sole power plant has shut down after running out of fuel. There is now no electricity in Gaza other than what can be produced with smaller-scale generators, which are being used to power hospitals and other essential facilities but also have limited fuel. Israel on Monday cut off Gaza's external electricity supply as part of its retaliation for the terror attacks perpetrated by Hamas in southern Israel over the weekend.
